#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
drop — static-artifact publishing CLI for a self-hosted `drop` deployment.

The CLI owns the local no-leak preflight and orchestration. The Worker (see
../worker) owns public serving, auth, expiry, revoke, and the canonical D1
manifest.

Configuration is via environment variables (a macOS keychain fallback is an
optional convenience — see README.md):

  Required
    DROP_BASE_URL               base URL of your deployed Worker, e.g.
                                https://drop.example.com  (no trailing slash needed)
    DROP_CF_ACCOUNT_ID          your Cloudflare account id (an identifier, not a
                                secret) — used to address R2's S3 endpoint
    DROP_R2_ACCESS_KEY_ID       S3 Access Key ID of a bucket-scoped R2
                                "Object Read & Write" token
    DROP_R2_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY   the matching S3 secret
    DROP_ADMIN_TOKEN            bearer token gating the Worker's /admin/* routes

  Optional
    DROP_R2_BUCKET              artifact bucket name (default: drop-artifacts)
    DROP_FORBIDDEN_R2_BUCKET    a bucket the upload creds must NOT reach; enables
                                the `drop scope-test` blast-radius check
    DROP_GITLEAKS_CONFIG        path to a gitleaks config (default: the bundled
                                drop-gitleaks.toml next to this script)
    DROP_KEYCHAIN_ACCOUNT       macOS keychain account to read secrets under
    DROP_*_KEYCHAIN             override the keychain service name for each secret
"""

